{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"951"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/951"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.1,0.16,0.22,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/951"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91871"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3670"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of diarrhoea. She had a similar episode three months ago following antibiotics for acute cholecystitis, which was diagnosed as \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection and successfully treated with oral vancomycin for two weeks. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. There has been no recent antibiotic exposure or other clear precipitant for this recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild generalised tenderness. Stool testing confirms recurrent \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous vancomycin","Oral metronidazole","Oral fidaxomicin","Oral vancomycin","Faecal microbiota transplantation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with her first recurrence of \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection. According to the 2025 Australasian Society of Infectious Diseases updated guidelines for the management of \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection in adults and children in Australia and New Zealand, the choice of antimicrobial therapy for recurrent infection depends on which drug resolved the initial episode and whether a clear precipitant can be identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fidaxomicin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment for this patient. Since her initial episode was successfully treated with vancomycin and there is no clear precipitant for this recurrence, fidaxomicin is recommended according to the 2025 guidelines. Fidaxomicin is a macrocyclic antibiotic with minimal systemic absorption and high faecal concentrations. However, it is important to note that fidaxomicin is not currently funded on the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme in Australia, which may affect its accessibility and affordability for patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there had been a clear precipitant (such as recent antibiotic exposure) or if the initial episode had been treated with metronidazole. However, in this case, with no apparent trigger and previous vancomycin treatment, fidaxomicin is preferred to reduce the risk of further recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective for recurrent disease. Current guidelines favour vancomycin or fidaxomicin due to their superior efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is ineffective for \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection as it does not achieve adequate concentrations in the colonic lumen where the infection occurs. Oral vancomycin is required for treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal microbiota transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with multiple recurrences or those who have failed fidaxomicin therapy. While highly effective with cure rates exceeding 90%, it is not indicated for a first recurrence when other antimicrobial options remain available.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fidaxomicin is recommended for recurrent Clostridioides difficile infection when the initial episode was resolved with vancomycin and no clear precipitant is identified.","Faecal microbiota transplantation is reserved for cases that have failed fidaxomicin therapy or for multiple recurrences."],"references":["Longhitano A, Roder C, Blackmore T, Campbell A, May M, Athan E. Australasian Society of Infectious Diseases updated guidelines for the management of Clostridioides difficile infection in adults and children in Australia and New Zealand. Intern Med J. 2025 Mar;55(3):503-513. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/imj.16638"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91871"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"951"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91871"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T21:56:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T21:57:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"951"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109501"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"